Every client interaction I have at work is exactly like the one I just had. So our senior developer has been working on a project with All State and they need to FTP some files back and forth. SFTP technically but it doesn't matter. It hasn't been working, and they of course insist it's all set up right on their side. So I verify she can FTP out to public sites, and for the hell of it make sure I can too. We can since we're in a vlan allowed to FTP externally. I then tracert to the client address to show the failure is happening past our firewall and at their IP space. Last I take a screencap of me searching our firewall for any instance of their IP range so they can see it's not being blocked. So we get a phone meeting where they get their network staff online . . . and it works. And they insist nothing changed, and casually ask if someone on our end maybe finally fixed something because the're unaware I'm the entire team and the only one who can change anything, where as they have a firewall team, router team, probably someone handling the server itself, maybe another security group, etc. It could be anyone in their chain who never gave us access so they assume they can just claim it was someone in our many teams who dropped the ball not realizing it's just me.
